1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,050
She didn't like teaching, so the pupils didn't like learning.

2
00:00:04,960 --> 00:00:08,530
But the second teacher had high, positive standards.

3
00:00:08,720 --> 00:00:13,010
She sincerely liked the children and wanted them to accomplish much.

4
00:00:13,280 --> 00:00:15,889
She considered each one as an individual.

5
00:00:16,079 --> 00:00:21,970
She obtained discipline easily because, in everything she did, she was well-disciplined.

6
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:29,329
And in each case, the pupils adjusted their conduct to fit the examples set by the teachers.

7
00:00:30,640 --> 00:00:35,570
We find the same form of adjustment taking place every day in adult groups.

8
00:00:35,839 --> 00:00:45,010
During World War II, military chiefs continually observed that the highest morale was not found in units where commanders were easy,

9
00:00:45,040 --> 00:00:47,089
relaxed, and lackadaisical.

10
00:00:47,360 --> 00:00:54,530
Crack units were led by officers with high standards who enforced military regulations fairly and properly.

11
00:00:54,800 --> 00:01:00,530
Military personnel simply do not respect and admire officers with low standards.

12
00:01:01,040 --> 00:01:06,049
College students, too, take their cue from the examples set by the professors.

13
00:01:06,480 --> 00:01:15,089
Students under one professor cut classes, copy term papers, and connive in various ways to pass without serious study.

14
00:01:15,440 --> 00:01:21,570
But the same students under another professor willingly work extra hard to master the subject.

15
00:01:22,400 --> 00:01:29,329
In business situations, we again find individuals patterning their thinking after that of the superior.

16
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:32,369
Study a group of employees closely.

17
00:01:32,480 --> 00:01:38,530
Observe their habits, mannerisms, attitudes toward the company, ethics, self-control.

18
00:01:38,880 --> 00:01:45,650
Then, compare what you find with the behavior of their superior, and you discover amazing similarities.

19
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:51,970
Every year, many corporations that have grown sluggish and are headed downward are rebuilt.

20
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:52,770
And how?

21
00:01:52,960 --> 00:01:56,450
By changing a handful of executives at the top.

22
00:01:56,880 --> 00:02:06,930
Companies, and colleges, and churches, and clubs, and unions, and all other types of organizations are successfully rebuilt from the top down,

23
00:02:07,040 --> 00:02:08,609
not from the bottom up.

24
00:02:08,960 --> 00:02:13,970
Change the thinking at the top, and you automatically change the thinking at the bottom.

25
00:02:14,640 --> 00:02:15,730
Remember this.

26
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:24,609
When you take over the leadership of a group, the persons in that group immediately begin to adjust themselves to the standards you set.

27
00:02:25,040 --> 00:02:28,210
This is most noticeable during the first few weeks.

28
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:34,050
Their big concern is to clue you in, zero you in, find out what you expect of them.

29
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:36,530
They watch every move you make.

30
00:02:36,640 --> 00:02:39,570
They think, how much rope will he give me?

31
00:02:39,760 --> 00:02:41,410
How does he want it done?

32
00:02:41,520 --> 00:02:43,490
What does it take to please him?

33
00:02:43,599 --> 00:02:46,370
What will he say if I do this or that?

34
00:02:46,959 --> 00:02:49,809
Once they know, they act accordingly.

35
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:52,370
Check the example you set.

36
00:02:52,559 --> 00:02:56,689
Use this old but ever-accurate quatrain as a guide.

37
00:02:57,199 --> 00:03:02,930
What kind of world would this world be, if everyone in it were just like me?

38
00:03:03,439 --> 00:03:06,570
To add meaning to this self-imposed test, substitute the word company for world so it reads,
